<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870429-0181 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:Corporate Citizen</HL><DD> 04/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> IBM </IN><TEXT>   Your page-one article (April 8) about the closing of the IBM plant in Greencastle, Ind., neglected to provide readers with a number of important facts. IBM donated the facility, as well as a substantial amount of real estate, to Greencastle. In addition, the company made cash contributions in excess of $1.5 million to the community to ease the tax burden. Also, it made very generous advance contributions to the United Way of Greencastle and to surrounding communities.    Of particular note is the amount of corporate citizenship exercised by IBM in 1976 when management decided not to close the Greencastle facility. While this would have been a sound economic decision, such a closure at that time would have been devastating to the community and to the employees. Most of the workers were at a low-skill base and it would have been virtually impossible to relocate them. Instead, IBM decided to upgrade the plant and skills of their employees through sizable investments.    Compared with GMC and a few steel companies, IBM is a &quot;lily of the valley,&quot; (the Wabash Valley, that is).    Prof. Larry D. Coleman   Indiana State University   Terre Haute, Ind.</TEXT></DOC>